Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Trim and thinly slice
@scallions{2}, separating greens and whites. Melt @butter{2%tbsp} in a #small pot{}
over medium-high heat. Add @water{3/4%cup} and a pinch of @salt{pinch}.
Bring to a boil, then add @basmati rice{1/2%cup}. Cover, lower heat, and reduce
to a simmer. Cook until tender, about ~{15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, peel @carrots{2}. Using your #peeler{}, shave carrots lengthwise into
ribbons over a #medium bowl{}, rotating until you get to the cores; discard
cores.

Add @white wine vinegar{5%tsp} and @sugar{1%tsp} to #bowl{} with carrots, then
season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat, cover with #plastic wrap{},
and keep refrigerated until you prep lunch in the morning.

Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium-high
heat. Pat @pork chops{24%oz} dry with a #paper towel{}; season all over with
salt, pepper, and @Thai seasoning blend{1%tbsp}. Add to pan and cook until
just browned, ~{2-3%minutes} per side. Transfer to one side of a foil-lined
#baking sheet{}.

Add scallion whites to pan used for pork over medium-high heat. Cook until
softened, about ~{30%seconds}. Stir in @soy sauce{2%tbsp}, @honey{1.5%oz},
@water{1%tbsp}, and up to @sriracha{4%tsp} (to taste; save remainder for lunch).
Scrape up any browned bits on bottom of pan. Let simmer until thick and sticky,
about ~{2%minutes}. If sauce gets too thick, stir in another 1-2 TBSP.
Remove pan from heat, then stir in @sesame oil{1%tbsp}.

Trim any tough ends from @sugar snap peas{6%oz}, then place on empty side of
baking sheet with pork. Toss with a large drizzle of oil and season with
plenty of salt and pepper. Set aside ⅓ of the glaze in a #small bowl{} and save
for lunch. Brush top of pork with half the remaining glaze. Roast in oven on
middle rack until snap peas are tender and pork reaches desired doneness,
~{7-10%minutes}.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}, then stir in half the scallion greens. Season with
salt and pepper. Divide between plates, then arrange 2 pork chops on top (save
the others for lunch). Add snap peas to the side. Spoon remaining half of glaze
over everything. Garnish with remaining scallion greens. Store remaining
ingredients until you're ready to prep lunch in the morning.

== Lunch Bánh Mì ==

Split @demi-baguette{2} lengthwise. Thinly slice reserved pork. Spread reserved
glaze in bowl onto baguette bottoms, then arrange pork on top. Tear
@cilantro{1/4%oz}(leaves torn from stems) and lay carrots on top. Spread baguette
tops with @sour cream{4%tbsp} and remaining @sriracha{2%tsp} and place on top to
create sandwiches. Wrap up and keep refrigerated until ready to eat.

> The Banh Mi Lunch Sandwich nutrition: 500 calories, 18g fat, 6g saturated fat,
> 56g carbohydrate, 18g sugar, 3g fiber, 25g protein, 75mg cholesterol, 830mg sodium.
